--- title: "Land Use/Land Cover and Watershed Maps" author: "Corinna Hong" date: "February 18, 2020" output: html_document banner: "img/banners/oahu.jfif" ---

This project maps different spatial data from Hawaii Statewide GIS Programâ€™s datasets. One map features a few different land use/land cover types on Oahu and another shows the top 10 largest watersheds on Oahu. The datasets used for these maps included spatial data for all eight Hawaiian Islands. In order to only showcase Oahu, the map area was cropped, then filtered to only include the data I wanted to display. The maps are also interactive, allowing users to zoom in and out.

# Load packages

# General
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(paletteer)

# Spatial
library(sf)
library(tmap)
# Read in data

land_use <- read_sf(dsn = here("Land_Use_Land_Cover_LULC"), layer = "Land_Use_Land_Cover_LULC")

watersheds <- read_sf(dsn = here("Watersheds"), layer = "Watersheds")

# st_crs(watersheds) checking CRS, both are EPSG: 4326
# Wrangle data for land cover

land_cover_oahu <- land_use %>%
  dplyr::select(landcover) %>%
  filter(landcover != 0) %>%  # Remove land use category of 0
  filter(landcover =="Residential"| landcover == "Commercial and Services" | landcover == "Bays and Estuaries" | landcover == "Evergreen Forest Land") %>% 
  st_crop(xmin = -158.31, xmax = -157.62, ymin = 21.26, ymax = 21.75)  # Crop to Oahu
# Create map for land use

oahu_map <- tm_basemap("Esri.WorldTopoMap") + # Add basemap
  tm_shape(land_cover_oahu) + # Add land cover
  tm_fill("landcover", title = "Land Cover", alpha = 0.6) # layer elements

tmap_mode("view")

oahu_map

Figure 1. Land Use Land Cover Types on Oahu. Location of bays and estuaries, commercial, evergreen forest, and residential land use/land cover (LULC) types based on historical LULC classification data as of 1976. Data accessed at: http://geoportal.hawaii.gov/datasets/land-use-land-cover-lulc?geometry=-165.822%2C18.755%2C-149.134%2C22.354 

# Wrangle data for watersheds

watersheds_oahu <- watersheds %>% 
  dplyr::select(wuname, hucarea) %>% 
  st_crop(xmin = -158.31, xmax = -157.62, ymin = 21.26, ymax = 21.75) %>%  # Crop to Oahu
  arrange(-hucarea) %>%  # arrange from largest to smallest area in square meters
  head(10) # Gives top 10
# Create map of watersheds


oahu_watersheds <- tm_basemap("Esri.WorldTopoMap") +
  tm_shape(watersheds_oahu) +
  tm_fill("wuname", title = "Watershed", alpha = 0.5)


tmap_mode("view")

oahu_watersheds

Figure 2. Oahuâ€™s Watersheds. Top 10 largest watersheds of Oahu layered over ESRI World Topomap. Area of watersheds are measured in square meters as calculated by the GIS. Data accessed at: http://geoportal.hawaii.gov/datasets/watersheds?geometry=-165.822%2C18.755%2C-149.134%2C22.354


References
Hawaii Statewide GIS Program. (2017). Land Use Land Cover (LULC). Available from http://geoportal.hawaii.gov/datasets/land-use-land-cover-lulc


Hawaii Statewide GIS Program. (2017). Surface Water Hydrologic Unit Boundaries (Watersheds). Available from : http://geoportal.hawaii.gov/datasets/watersheds
